$d = l\sqrt{2} 
Arr l = \frac{20}{\sqrt{2}}$.
$\therefore$ Perimeter = $(4l)$ cm = $\left(4 \times \frac{20}{\sqrt{2}} \times \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}}\right)$ cm = $40\sqrt{2}$ cm.

Let the length of sides of the two triangles be $a_1$ and $a_2$ respectively and their altitudes be $h_1$ and $h_2$ respectively.
Then, $\frac{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} a_1^2}{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} a_2^2} = \frac{25}{36} 
$\Leftrightarrow \left(\frac{a_1}{a_2}\right)^2 = \left(\frac{5}{6}\right)^2 
$\Leftrightarrow \frac{a_1}{a_2} = \frac{5}{6}$.
And, $\frac{\frac{1}{2} a_1 h_1}{\frac{1}{2} a_2 h_2} = \frac{25}{36} 
$\Leftrightarrow \frac{5}{6} \times \frac{h_1}{h_2} = \frac{25}{36} 
$\Leftrightarrow \frac{h_1}{h_2} = \frac{25}{36} \times \frac{6}{5} = \frac{5}{6}$.

Let the area of each be $a$. Then,
radius of the circle = $\sqrt{\frac{a}{\pi}}$; side of the square = $\sqrt{a}$;
side of the triangle = $\sqrt{\frac{a\times4}{\sqrt{3}}}$.
Perimeter of the circle = $2\pi\sqrt{\frac{a}{\pi}} = 2\sqrt{\pi a} = 2\sqrt{3.14}a = 2\times1.77\sqrt{a} = 3.54\sqrt{a}$.
Perimeter of the square = $4\sqrt{a}$;
Perimeter of the triangle = $3\times\sqrt{\frac{4a}{\sqrt{3}}} = 3\times\frac{2\sqrt{a}}{1.732} = 3\times1.52\sqrt{a} = 4.56\sqrt{a}$.
